# Error Handling

You must strictly enforce these error handling standards during the implementation phase. Code that violates these rules must fail the refactoring step.

## 1. Core Principles
- Handle errors explicitly — never ignore or silently swallow failures.
- Fail fast when required inputs, dependencies, or configurations are invalid — validate at the boundary, not deep in the call stack.
- Catch errors only when you can meaningfully handle, recover, enrich, or provide a fallback. Otherwise re-throw.
- When re-throwing or wrapping an error, always preserve the original error — via the native `{ cause }` option (ES2022+) or your project's established wrapping pattern. Never discard it.

```js
catch (err) { throw new Error('Something went wrong'); } // Bad — root cause lost

catch (err) { throw new DatabaseError('Failed to fetch user', { cause: err }); } // Good
catch (err) { throw new DatabaseError('Failed to fetch user', { originalError: err }); } // Also valid
```

## 2. Async Error Handling
- Always wrap `async/await` calls in `try/catch` at the appropriate boundary.
- Never leave a `Promise` without an error path — floating promises are silent failures.
- Use `finally` for cleanup regardless of success or failure.
- Use `Promise.allSettled()` instead of `Promise.all()` when partial failures are acceptable.

```js
fetchUser(id).then(updateProfile); // Bad — unhandled rejection

try { // Good
  const user = await fetchUser(id);
  await updateProfile(user);
} catch (err) {
  logger.error('Failed to update profile', { userId: id, err });
  throw err;
} finally {
  releaseConnection();
}
```

## 3. Custom Error Classes
- If the project already has an established error class hierarchy or error library (`http-errors`, `boom`, or internal module), follow that pattern — never introduce a parallel error system.
- Only create new error classes when no established pattern exists or a new domain concept needs distinct upstream handling.
- Extend the native `Error` class — name errors after the domain concept, not the technical layer.

```js
class ValidationError extends Error {
  constructor(message, { cause, field } = {}) {
    super(message, { cause });
    this.name = 'ValidationError';
    this.field = field;
  }
}

class NotFoundError extends Error {
  constructor(resource, id) {
    super(`${resource} with id ${id} not found`);
    this.name = 'NotFoundError';
  }
}
```

## 4. Error Boundaries & Top-Level Handlers
- In Express/Node.js: use centralized error-handling middleware as the last middleware — never handle all errors inline in route handlers.
- In React: wrap feature subtrees in Error Boundaries to prevent a single component failure from crashing the entire app.
- Register `process.on('unhandledRejection')` and `process.on('uncaughtException')` in Node.js entry points.

## 5. Empty & Shallow Catch Blocks
- Never use empty `catch` blocks — at minimum, log the error with context.
- Never catch an error just to re-throw the same generic message — add context or don't catch.

```js
try { await saveOrder(order); } catch (err) {} // Bad — swallowed

try { await saveOrder(order); } catch (err) { throw new Error('Error saving order'); } // Bad — no added value

try { // Good
  await saveOrder(order);
} catch (err) {
  throw new OrderPersistenceError(`Failed to save order ${order.id}`, { cause: err });
}
```

## 6. Logging
- Log errors with enough context to reproduce the issue — include relevant IDs, operation name, and the original error.
- Never log sensitive values — passwords, tokens, API keys, PII, payment data.
- Log at the handling boundary only — not at every layer the error passes through.

## 7. User-Facing Errors
- Never expose stack traces, internal error messages, or infrastructure details to end users.
- Map domain/technical errors to user-friendly messages at the API or UI boundary.

## 8. Retry Logic
- Only retry operations that are idempotent and fail due to transient conditions (network timeouts, rate limits, temporary unavailability).
- Never retry invalid input, authentication failures, or permanent errors.
- Always set a retry limit and use exponential backoff.
- Never silently retry — log the attempt and reason.

## Checklist
- No empty or comment-only catch blocks
- No swallowed exceptions — every catch either handles, enriches, or re-throws
- No floating promises — every async call has an error path
- `finally` used wherever cleanup is required
- Re-thrown errors preserve the original error — never discarded
- Domain errors use custom error classes, not plain `new Error()`
- Top-level error handlers registered (Express middleware / React Error Boundary / unhandledRejection)
- Errors logged with context at the handling boundary only — not at every layer
- No sensitive data in error logs
- No stack traces or internal details exposed to end users
- Retry logic only applied to idempotent, transient failures — with attempt limits and backoff
